definition.value: A deoxyhexose comprising glucose having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
Any C6 deoxy sugar having at least one hydroxy group replaced by hydrogen.
Any sugar having a hydroxy group replaced with a hydrogen atom.
A natural or synthetic compound having a sequence of amino and hydroxy carboxylic acid residues (usually alpha-amino and alpha-hydroxy acids), commonly but not necessarily regularly alternating.
Glucans produced by the hydrolysis of starch or glycogen. They are mixtures of polymers of D-glucose units linked by alpha(1->4) or alpha(1->6) glycosidic bonds.
Any polyamine that contains two amino groups.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the conjugate base of 2,6-diaminopimelic acid.
The amino dicarboxylic acid that is heptanedioic acid with amino aubstituents at C-2 and C-6.
An azole that is either one of a pair of heterocyclic organic compounds comprising three carbon atoms and two nitrogen atoms arranged in a ring.
Any member of the class of chlorobenzenes carrying two chloro groups at unspecified positions.
Any chlorophenol carrying chloro substituents.
The uridine derivative obtained by formal hydrogenation of the endocyclic double bond in the uracil ring.
Any member of the class of  hydroxybenzoic acids carrying  two phenolic hydroxy groups on the benzene ring and its derivatives.
A hydroxyproline that is proline substituted by two hydroxy substituents.
A compound that contains two hydroxy groups, generally assumed to be, but not necessarily, alcoholic. Aliphatic diols are also called glycols.

Any terpenoid derived from a diterpene. The term includes compounds in which the C20 skeleton of the parent diterpene has been rearranged or modified by the removal of one or more skeletal atoms (generally methyl groups).
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of behenic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.

Any member of the group of signalling molecules arising from oxidation of the three C20 essential fatty acids (EFAs) icosapentaenoic acid (EPA), arachidonic acid (AA) and dihomo-gamma-linolenic acid (DGLA).
Any diol that is ethane or substituted ethane carrying two hydroxy groups.
Any carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid with ethanol.
An aliphatic sulfide in which the sulfur atom is bonded to at least one ethyl group.

Amfenac in which the the hydrogen at the 4 position of the benzoyl group is substituted by bromine. It is used for the management of ocular pain and treatment of postoperative inflammation in patients who have undergone cataract extraction. It was withdrawn from the US market in 1998, following concerns over off-label abuse and hepatic failure.
An aliphatic alcohol consisting of a chain of 8 to 22 carbon atoms. Fatty alcohols may be saturated or unsaturated and may be branched or unbranched.
A member of the class of flavonoid with a 2-aryl-1-benzopyran-4-one (2-arylchromen-4-one) skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
Amides with the general formula R(1)R(2)NCHO (R(1) and R(2) can be H).
A substance used to destroy fungal pests.
Compounds containing at least one furan ring.
A phosphatidylcholine where the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as tetradecanoyl (myristoyl).
A heteroglycan that consists of a backbone of randomly distributed (1->4)-linked mannose and glucose units with (1->6)-linked galactose units attached to mannose units.
